Homework #2 Solutions STAT 506 Spring 2015

  1. Researchers in Jordan are interested in plants useable for animal fodder which require little moisture. They tested four plant species in a greenhouse experiment varying the daily watering from 50 to 650 mm in 100 mm increments. Within each species, water amounts were allocated at random. The response is dry biomass. Read in the data here

    1. Plot the data in a manner which allows us to easily compare median biomass for each species as a function of water.

    2. Fit a model with an intercept and the interaction model: \[ y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \alpha_{0j[i]} + \alpha_{1j[i]} x_i + \epsilon_i\]
      In this notation, \(i\) is the row number, \(j[i]\) is the plant species of the plant in row \(i\) (\(j = 1\) to 4), \(\beta\)s are overall effects, and \(\alpha\)s are adjustments for each plant species.

      1. Fit this model in SAS and show the estimated coefficients.

      2. Provide either the Type I or Type III output table, and explain why you think this table is preferred. Is the interaction needed?
        I would favor Type I sums of squares because it makes no sense to look at the need for a main effect when the model includes an interaction of that main effect and some other predictor. However, this is balanced data, so the columns of X are orthogonal, and ordering doesnt matter.

      3. What combination of Greek letters is estimated by each coefficient shown?

        \(\beta_0 + \alpha_{04}\) is estimated as 3.995 (SE 0.35)
        \(\hat{\alpha}_{01} - \hat{\alpha}_{04} = 2.39 \) (SE 0.50)
        \(\hat{\alpha}_{02} - \hat{\alpha}_{04} = 2.34 \) (SE 0.50)
        \(\hat{\alpha}_{03} - \hat{\alpha}_{04} = 0.90 \) (SE 0.0)
        \(\beta_1 + \alpha_{14}\) is estimated as 0.0059 (SE 0.0009)
        \(\hat{\alpha}_{11} - \hat{\alpha}_{14} = 0.0023 \) (SE 0.0012)
        \(\hat{\alpha}_{12} -\hat{ \alpha}_{14} = 0.0018 \) (SE 0.0012)
        \(\hat{\alpha}_{13} - \hat{\alpha}_{14} = 0.00029 \) (SE 0.0012)

      Plot the four lines.

      Slopes appear to be quite similar, which makes sense since the interaction term
      has a large p-value.

      The default diagnostic plots:

      Having taken square root, I see no problem with the diagnostic plots. These data look quite normal and seem to have constant spread.

  2. Sitka Trees from MASS package

    1. Plot size over time, separating the two groups, and using a different line for each individual tree.

    2. Use PROC MIXED to fit a quadratic model across all the data. Do we need intercept, slope, and/or quadratic coefficients to depend on treatment? As in R, use REML (the default) when comparing random effects, ML for fixed effects.
      I centered the time variable before squaring it. The interaction between time and treatment is quite strong, (\(t_{313} = 4.59\), p-value < .001) indicating that the trees grew faster in the control environment rather than with ozone. The coefficient on time squared has a t-ratio of -11.8, and another tiny p-value. I conclude that there is a quadratic trend, but the difference between ozone and control is mainly in the linear component. AIC for this model is 73.9. Adding random slopes reduced AICc to -2.3, which indicates the random slopes are needed in the model.

    3. The only ACF plot Im finding in SAS is in PROC MI (multiple imputation), and I think it refers to MCMC sequences. Thats not helpful. So we may have to do it blindly. Fit the same model(s) for correlation as you did in R by using PROC MIXED. Compare with the models in (a).

      I fit AR(1) and unstructured correlations. The AR(1) gives an estimate of \(\hat{\phi} = 1\) which cant be right, and AIC goes way up to 214, and the residuals versus fitted plot now shows a curved pattern. On the other hand, the unstructured covariance returned a reasonable value and reduced AICc quite a bit more to -44.4. It seems to be the best model.

    4. After finding a model with reasonable correlation structure, see if you can prune back the fixed effects. Provide diagnostic plots and explain your model.

      No, we cant reduce the fixed effects. The p-values for time squared (<.001) and for treatment by time (linear) interaction (0.006) are still very small, so we need to keep the full model.

    5. Compare to the results from HW5 last fall.

      R fit estimated the treatment by time effect to be -0.0023, SE = 0.00058 while SAS says its -0.0021, SE = 0.00077, so they are very similar.

      Tree to tree variance estimates: 0.74 for intercept, 8.6e-6 for slope. I didnt get convergence on this model in R, but the random intercept model estimated variance of 0.389.

SAS Code

Plant Biomass data

 datafile= "/folders/myfolders/Stat506/plantBiomass.csv"; 
  out=biomass   dbms=dlm    replace;
  delimiter=',' ;
  getnames=yes;
run;
* proc contents;
run;
Proc Sort data = biomass;
  by species;
run;

proc sgpanel data= biomass;
  panelby species;
  vbox biomass / category= water;
run;

PROC Freq data = biomass;
   table species;
run;
DATA biomass;
  set biomass;
  sqrtMass = sqrt(biomass);
run;
PROC GLM data = biomass plot = diagnostics;
  class species;
  model sqrtMass = species | water/ solution ss1 ;
run;

Sitka Spruce Trees SAS Code printed through R

  ## with code chunk option:  comment=""
temp <- scan(file="SitkaTrees.sas", what = "a", sep = "\n")
cat(paste(temp,"\n"))
Data Sitka; 
   infile "/folders/myfolders/sitka.txt" firstobs = 2; 
     input size time tree treat$; 
     timeSq = (time - 202)**2; 
 title ""; 
  PROC SORT; 
   by treat tree; 
 run; 
   /*proc means mean; 
     by treat; 
     run; 
   */   
 proc sgpanel data = sitka; 
   panelby treat; 
   series x=time y = size / group = tree; 
 run; 
 title "Random Intercept"; 
    PROC MIXED data = sitka plots = residualpanel; 
     class treat ; 
     model size = time | treat timeSq / s; 
     random int / subject = tree ; 
     run; 
 title "Random Slope and Intercept"; 
      PROC MIXED data = sitka plots = residualpanel; 
     class treat ; 
     model size = time | treat timeSq / s; 
     random int time / subject = tree; 
     run; 
 title "Add AR(1)"; 
      
    PROC MIXED data = sitka plots = residualpanel; 
     class treat ; 
     model size = time | treat timeSq / s; 
     random int time / subject = tree type = ar(1); 
     run; 
      
 title "Add Unstructured Correlations"; 
      
    PROC MIXED data = sitka plots = residualpanel; 
     class treat ; 
     model size = time | treat timeSq / s; 
     random int time / subject = tree type = un; 
     run;
